    "target": "@team-lead",
    "targetColor": "red",
    "summary": "Option B — virtue in quote, character in analysis",
    "content": "**Option B.** This is the right answer for a precise reason:\n\nThe author explicitly states the 道德仁义礼 passage is \"并非对《老子》的解释\" -- it is NOT an interpretation of Laozi. The Laozi quotation is a *source text* that the author then *re-analyzes* in their own framework. These are two different speech acts: quoting and analyzing.\n\nThe block quote is Laozi's words. Use \"virtue\" -- it is the established rendering, the reader recognizes it, and we are not the ones translating the Dao De Jing. The moment the author begins their own analysis (\"然而，礼事实上是从现象所总结出来的...\"), switch to \"(constitutive) character.\" A brief TN at the transition: \"The author now departs from the traditional reading. Where 德 in the Laozi quotation is rendered as 'virtue' following standard convention, the author's own analysis uses '(constitutive) character' to reflect their constructivist reinterpretation of 德 as the defining properties abstracted from phenomena, not moral excellence.\"\n\nThis actually *strengthens* the philosophical experiment. The reader first sees the familiar \"virtue\" in the classical text, then watches the author dismantle and reconstruct it as \"character.\" The terminological shift *enacts* the conceptual shift -- the reader experiences the inversion in real time through the change in vocabulary. Option A would hide this by using the same word throughout, flattening the very distinction the passage is trying to make visible.\n"
  }
}
